that ball and that's dangerous.

00:03:28.510 --> 00:03:30.800 align:middle line:90%
And so we yell, no!

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:32.570 align:middle line:84%
And every one of
you who just heard

00:03:32.570 --> 00:03:36.420 align:middle line:84%
that, I'm sure you felt a
slight tightening in your body.

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:40.060 align:middle line:84%
That turns off the motivational
center in the brain.

00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:42.640 align:middle line:84%
That stimulates the fear
circuit in the brain.

00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:45.410 align:middle line:84%
That sends out a different
set of the neurochemicals that

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:48.510 align:middle line:84%
literally stop you from moving
and make you turn around

00:03:48.510 --> 00:03:50.130 align:middle line:90%
and run in the other direction.

00:03:50.130 --> 00:03:51.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's so interesting.

00:03:51.380 --> 00:03:53.430 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to look at a
lot of this on the screen--

00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:53.810 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:03:53.810 --> 00:03:55.780 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --so we can see
what this looks like.

00:03:55.780 --> 00:03:58.320 align:middle line:84%
So tell me what this
first image looks like?

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:00.670 align:middle line:90%
It's spectacular in color.

00:04:00.670 --> 00:04:01.810 align:middle line:90%
What are we looking at?

00:04:01.810 --> 00:04:04.150 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Now, color doesn't
really exist in the brain.

00:04:04.150 --> 00:04:07.960 align:middle line:84%
But there's a new project called
the Human Connectome Project.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:10.040 align:middle line:84%
And what we're doing--
it's the same thing

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:11.720 align:middle line:84%
that the geneticists
did in terms

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:14.160 align:middle line:84%
of mapping out the
human genome system.

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.290 align:middle line:84%
But with the human brain,
you've got 85 billion neurons,

00:04:17.290 --> 00:04:19.470 align:middle line:90%
you have 85 billion glial cells.

00:04:19.470 --> 00:04:22.100 align:middle line:84%
I'll talk about those
a little bit later.

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:24.190 align:middle line:84%
But what you are
actually seeing here

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:27.520 align:middle line:84%
is that you need to understand
that a single neuron

00:04:27.520 --> 00:04:30.800 align:middle line:84%
in our frontal lobes where our
thought processes take place,

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:32.720 align:middle line:84%
where my imagination
takes place, where

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:35.250 align:middle line:84%
my decision-making
process take place,

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:37.650 align:middle line:84%
these neurons can
send connections

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:40.610 align:middle line:84%
all the way back to the
brain, to the furtherest back.

00:04:40.610 --> 00:04:42.480 align:middle line:84%
So what you are
actually seeing is

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:45.900 align:middle line:84%
all of the connections that
take place in your frontal lobes

00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:48.290 align:middle line:84%
where consciousness
actually exists

00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:51.160 align:middle line:84%
and how it spreads back
through the rest of your brain.

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:55.601 align:middle line:84%
And this is only a partial view
of how many connections there

00:04:55.601 --> 00:04:56.100 align:middle line:90%
are.

00:04:56.100 --> 00:04:58.620 align:middle line:84%
A single neuron can
make connections

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:02.460 align:middle line:84%
with 10,000 other neurons
at one particular time.

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:06.290 align:middle line:84%
So this means that there is
no one part of the brain.

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:08.330 align:middle line:84%
Years ago, you see
a model and they

00:05:08.330 --> 00:05:12.080 align:middle line:84%
would call this your visual
cortex and your parietal lobe.

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:13.960 align:middle line:90%
These are arbitrary lines.

00:05:13.960 --> 00:05:16.200 align:middle line:84%
But if neurons are
interconnecting

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:19.120 align:middle line:84%
and interweaving and flowing,
where do you divide the line?

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:22.950 align:middle line:84%
Where does this frontal lobe end
and your visual cortex begin?

00:05:22.950 --> 00:05:24.960 align:middle line:90%
It all blurs together.

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:29.060 align:middle line:84%
So we have to understand
that this is a interconnected

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:32.000 align:middle line:84%
system that has no
beginning or end.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.340 align:middle line:84%
Every part is constantly
interacting and communicating

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:36.370 align:middle line:90%
with every other part.

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:38.703 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So when people talk
about quadrants of the brain

00:05:38.703 --> 00:05:41.440 align:middle line:84%
and the frontal lobe
and so forth, it's--

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:42.790 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Made up language.

00:05:42.790 --> 00:05:43.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:44.276 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Made up language.

00:05:44.276 --> 00:05:46.520 align:middle line:84%
It's like to say, well, we
have to talk about-- well,

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:48.320 align:middle line:84%
there is this
particular area where

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:50.670 align:middle line:84%
we notice that
consciousness begins.

00:05:50.670 --> 00:05:54.400 align:middle line:84%
And they'll call it the
dorsolateral prefrontal cortex.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:55.900 align:middle line:84%
And you have to
figure out that that

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:59.200 align:middle line:84%
goes into the frontal lobes or
up into this particular point

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:00.620 align:middle line:90%
right here.

00:06:00.620 --> 00:06:03.480 align:middle line:84%
But it's better to
see these new images.

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:05.480 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So this image
that we're looking at here

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:08.150 align:middle line:84%
is from the brain
imaging center.

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:09.650 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
center that you were

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:12.500 align:middle line:84%
talking about that created these
different types of graphics.

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:15.090 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: So why I want to show
you this is that in the past

00:06:15.090 --> 00:06:18.130 align:middle line:84%
there has been a rumor--
it's never been true.

00:06:18.130 --> 00:06:20.900 align:middle line:84%
There's never been right
brain thinking and left brain

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:21.570 align:middle line:90%
thinking.

00:06:21.570 --> 00:06:24.750 align:middle line:84%
There's always
interhemispheric dialogue

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:26.290 align:middle line:90%
going on at both times.

00:06:26.290 --> 00:06:28.950 align:middle line:84%
And what you are actually
seeing are the connections

00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:32.250 align:middle line:84%
that go from one side
of the hemisphere

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:36.290 align:middle line:84%
through the center part of your
brain, over to the other side.

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:39.870 align:middle line:84%
So again, there is this constant
dialogue and communication

00:06:39.870 --> 00:06:42.280 align:middle line:84%
going back and forth
instantaneously

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:44.240 align:middle line:84%
between the front
side of your brain

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:46.510 align:middle line:84%
and the back side of your
brain, between the left side

00:06:46.510 --> 00:06:48.760 align:middle line:84%
of your brain and the
right side of your brain.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:51.840 align:middle line:84%
You do have two completely
separate hemispheres.

00:06:51.840 --> 00:06:54.680 align:middle line:84%
And each one looks at the
world in a different way.

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:56.820 align:middle line:84%
But they're also
dialogueing with each other

00:06:56.820 --> 00:07:00.160 align:middle line:84%
all the time to create
a unified picture

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:01.770 align:middle line:90%
of the world we think we see.

00:07:01.770 --> 00:07:03.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:07:03.090 --> 00:07:03.590 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:05.885 align:middle line:84%
So we've heard of the
language center of the brain

00:07:05.885 --> 00:07:09.440 align:middle line:84%
and areas of the brain that
are responsible for emotions

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:11.462 align:middle line:90%
and communication.

00:07:11.462 --> 00:07:12.920 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: And
we're just beginning

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:15.140 align:middle line:84%
to map out some of
the primary emotions.

00:07:15.140 --> 00:07:17.340 align:middle line:84%
And there are very
specific circuits.

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:19.480 align:middle line:84%
You know what causes
us to be afraid,

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:21.850 align:middle line:84%
and what causes us
to be angry, and what

00:07:21.850 --> 00:07:24.890 align:middle line:84%
causes us to feel loving
and nurturing, each of these

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:28.150 align:middle line:84%
have now have been identified
as specific brain circuits.

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:30.280 align:middle line:84%
But they take place
in the lower part

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:34.840 align:middle line:84%
of our brain, where I can't even
show you many pictures of this

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:36.940 align:middle line:84%
because we don't have
brain scan technology

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:38.840 align:middle line:90%
to go down that deep.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:41.740 align:middle line:84%
But what happens is that
our primary emotions never

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:43.520 align:middle line:90%
make it into consciousness.

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:45.850 align:middle line:84%
Something else makes
it into consciousness.

00:07:45.850 --> 00:07:50.310 align:middle line:84%
And then we create a picture
of an emotional experience

00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:51.960 align:middle line:90%
that we've just had.

00:07:51.960 --> 00:07:54.760 align:middle line:84%
And so normally what
psychologists call emotions,

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:56.410 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to call feelings.

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:58.050 align:middle line:90%
And feelings aren't real.

00:07:58.050 --> 00:08:02.060 align:middle line:84%
So when I'm feeling happy
and I'm feeling sad,

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:04.470 align:middle line:84%
this is taking place
between one to 10 seconds

00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:08.220 align:middle line:84%
after I've had an emotional
experience of either pleasure

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:09.235 align:middle line:90%
or pain.

00:08:09.235 --> 00:08:11.500 align:middle line:84%
The lower part of the
brain is very simple.

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:13.670 align:middle line:84%
It's either pleasant
or it's unpleasant.

00:08:13.670 --> 00:08:15.864 align:middle line:84%
But then that frontal
lobe consciousness

00:08:15.864 --> 00:08:17.280 align:middle line:84%
and all those
connections that you

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:20.630 align:middle line:84%
saw in that first part
of that image over there,

00:08:20.630 --> 00:08:23.280 align:middle line:90%
it's translating that feeling.

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:26.200 align:middle line:84%
It's pulling up old
memories from the past.

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:28.410 align:middle line:84%
It's associating it
with old feelings

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:31.190 align:middle line:84%
that we've had in the
past and projecting it

00:08:31.190 --> 00:08:33.409 align:middle line:84%
onto what might
happen in the future.

00:08:33.409 --> 00:08:35.460 align:middle line:84%
Our frontal lobe
consciousness never even

00:08:35.460 --> 00:08:37.110 align:middle line:90%
lives in the present moment.

00:08:37.110 --> 00:08:40.289 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So where exactly
does consciousness

00:08:40.289 --> 00:08:41.510 align:middle line:90%
live in the brain?

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:43.064 align:middle line:90%
Is it located in the brain?

00:08:43.064 --> 00:08:43.689 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:08:43.689 --> 00:08:48.160 align:middle line:84%
We now know where it
exists, and how it emerges,

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:49.590 align:middle line:90%
and where comes from.

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:53.180 align:middle line:84%
It's true for all mammals
and probably all animals.

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:54.870 align:middle line:84%
Most neuroscientists--
there's even

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:57.200 align:middle line:84%
been a declaration
signed that we

00:08:57.200 --> 00:08:59.850 align:middle line:84%
have to consider
that all animals have

00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:03.580 align:middle line:84%
a form of consciousness similar
to what you and I have right

00:09:03.580 --> 00:09:04.580 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:09:04.580 --> 00:09:05.587 align:middle line:90%
And what happens--

00:09:05.587 --> 00:09:06.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:08.503 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: --in this lower
part of the brain, when

00:09:08.503 --> 00:09:11.800 align:middle line:84%
we feel something that creates
a pleasurable sensation,

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:13.870 align:middle line:84%
and that can be
something that's new,

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:15.980 align:middle line:84%
something that's
different, something

00:09:15.980 --> 00:09:20.460 align:middle line:84%
that arouses our curiosity,
something that smells sweet,

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:25.750 align:middle line:84%
looks aesthetic or beautiful,
and this releases dopamine

00:09:25.750 --> 00:09:28.940 align:middle line:84%
from a little tiny structure
called a nucleus accumbens.

00:09:28.940 --> 00:09:32.060 align:middle line:84%
And it releases dopamine in
the lower part of the brain.

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:33.810 align:middle line:90%
And guess where it all goes?

00:09:33.810 --> 00:09:35.840 align:middle line:84%
Right up there into
the frontal lobes.

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:38.160 align:middle line:90%
And this is what wakes you up.

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:40.740 align:middle line:84%
And if you take your
little tiny fingernails

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:43.810 align:middle line:84%
on your little tiny pinkie and
put one above each eye right

00:09:43.810 --> 00:09:47.950 align:middle line:84%
here, this is the
everyday consciousness

00:09:47.950 --> 00:09:50.000 align:middle line:84%
that you and I are
living in right now

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.990 align:middle line:84%
and that every viewer
watching this is operating on.

00:09:52.990 --> 00:09:56.250 align:middle line:84%
And it's almost a habitual
form of consciousness.

00:09:56.250 --> 00:09:57.980 align:middle line:90%
It's not very aware.

00:09:57.980 --> 00:10:00.640 align:middle line:84%
We are just processing and
we think we're seeing things

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:01.390 align:middle line:90%
and we're paying--

00:10:01.390 --> 00:10:01.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: We're awake.

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:03.210 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: --attention
to our words.

00:10:03.210 --> 00:10:03.810 align:middle line:90%
We're awake.

00:10:03.810 --> 00:10:04.780 align:middle line:90%
We're conscious.

00:10:04.780 --> 00:10:07.420 align:middle line:84%
And this is something
that all animals have.

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:10.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And is that also what
they call the alpha state?

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:14.300 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: We have to throw away
all of the EEG readings, which

00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:16.870 align:middle line:84%
only read the outermost
layer of the skull.

00:10:16.870 --> 00:10:20.110 align:middle line:84%
We now know there's over 52
different types of brain wave

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:22.750 align:middle line:84%
activities going on and they
change with every thought

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:25.690 align:middle line:84%
and feeling we have, second
to second to second to second.

00:10:25.690 --> 00:10:28.430 align:middle line:84%
So you maybe have an alpha
functioning going over here,

00:10:28.430 --> 00:10:29.225 align:middle line:90%
delta here,--

00:10:29.225 --> 00:10:29.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:10:29.960 --> 00:10:31.710 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: --gamma in
the back over here--

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:33.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:10:33.010 --> 00:10:35.410 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: --dissociative
brain waves down here.

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:40.290 align:middle line:84%
And we're abandoning
the EEG models

00:10:40.290 --> 00:10:43.670 align:middle line:84%
to understand more about
how these neurons begin

00:10:43.670 --> 00:10:47.970 align:middle line:84%
to become active or deactivated
during different thought

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:49.975 align:middle line:84%
process and experiences
that we have.

00:10:49.975 --> 00:10:51.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's fascinating.

00:10:51.100 --> 00:10:52.840 align:middle line:84%
So when we are talking
about accessing

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:54.450 align:middle line:90%
higher states of consciousness--

00:10:54.450 --> 00:10:56.600 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Ah, yes.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:10:58.442 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --is that
we're accessing or--

00:10:58.442 --> 00:10:59.025 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: No.

00:10:59.025 --> 00:10:59.580 align:middle line:90%
We're not.

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:01.840 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --increasing the levels
in our prefrontal cortex?

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:02.240 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:03.300 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Right
now, you are not

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:04.890 align:middle line:84%
in a higher state
of consciousness.

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:06.950 align:middle line:84%
I'm not in a higher
state of consciousness.

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:09.160 align:middle line:84%
There's not a listener
or a viewer out there

00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:12.274 align:middle line:84%
that's in a higher state
of consciousness right now.

00:11:12.274 --> 00:11:12.940 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Because?

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:15.050 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Because this
is ordinary processing

00:11:15.050 --> 00:11:17.590 align:middle line:84%
of information coming
in about the world

00:11:17.590 --> 00:11:19.230 align:middle line:84%
just to make sure
that we survive.

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:21.350 align:middle line:90%
So I remain standing up.

00:11:21.350 --> 00:11:25.330 align:middle line:84%
So I organize my words in such a
way that you can understand it.

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:28.150 align:middle line:90%
This is nothing unusual.

00:11:28.150 --> 00:11:30.640 align:middle line:84%
But we have found--
because what we're

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:33.290 align:middle line:84%
famous for is that
Andy Newberg and I,

00:11:33.290 --> 00:11:36.030 align:middle line:84%
we've done the brain scan
studies of nuns, and Buddhists,

00:11:36.030 --> 00:11:38.060 align:middle line:84%
and Pentecostals
speaking in tongues,

00:11:38.060 --> 00:11:42.420 align:middle line:84%
and atheists praying to God,
and people doing affirmations.

00:11:42.420 --> 00:11:45.760 align:middle line:84%
And what we find out is that
there are specific processes

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:48.110 align:middle line:90%
and activities that you can do.

00:11:48.110 --> 00:11:50.840 align:middle line:84%
And when you have the person
in a brain scan machine,

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:54.590 align:middle line:84%
you begin to see that these
two tiny areas of consciousness

00:11:54.590 --> 00:11:56.970 align:middle line:90%
begin to expand and grow.

00:11:56.970 --> 00:12:00.900 align:middle line:84%
You begin to bring online
more parts of frontal lobe

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:03.930 align:middle line:84%
functioning that
increases your awareness.

00:12:03.930 --> 00:12:08.300 align:middle line:84%
And this awareness is
outside of words or language.

00:12:08.300 --> 00:12:10.890 align:middle line:84%
So the book that I wrote,
"Words Can Change Your Brain,"

00:12:10.890 --> 00:12:14.110 align:middle line:84%
the interesting thing is
that of the eight most

00:12:14.110 --> 00:12:16.160 align:middle line:84%
essential elements
of communication,

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:17.854 align:middle line:90%
words are number eight.

00:12:17.854 --> 00:12:19.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, that's
so fascinating.

00:12:19.270 --> 00:12:22.310 align:middle line:84%
So we're taking a look here at
the frontal limbic filters--

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:24.810 align:middle line:84%
fibers-- that we were
talking about here.

00:12:24.810 --> 00:12:27.770 align:middle line:84%
So the states of consciousness
that you're saying

00:12:27.770 --> 00:12:29.585 align:middle line:90%
exist in a meditative state.

00:12:29.585 --> 00:12:30.210 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:12:30.210 --> 00:12:30.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:33.070 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Now, this slide
is particularly important

00:12:33.070 --> 00:12:35.860 align:middle line:84%
because here you see
everyday consciousness.

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:38.400 align:middle line:84%
And the moment you hold that
negative thought, the moment

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:40.750 align:middle line:84%
you heard the word
"no," or I say,

00:12:40.750 --> 00:12:42.930 align:middle line:84%
"oh, I don't feel
good this morning,"

00:12:42.930 --> 00:12:46.230 align:middle line:84%
even if you're making
it up, this information

00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:50.280 align:middle line:84%
gets sent into deeper
brain structures that

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:53.670 align:middle line:84%
activate a warning signal,
like in the amygdala.

00:12:53.670 --> 00:12:56.480 align:middle line:84%
So the moment you have
an imaginary fantasy

00:12:56.480 --> 00:13:00.701 align:middle line:84%
thought-- I'm worried about
what will happen tomorrow--

00:13:00.701 --> 00:13:02.450 align:middle line:84%
what happens is that
the rest of the brain

00:13:02.450 --> 00:13:04.790 align:middle line:90%
says this is happening today.

00:13:04.790 --> 00:13:06.240 align:middle line:90%
Put out an alarm.

00:13:06.240 --> 00:13:07.220 align:middle line:90%
Stop yourself.

00:13:07.220 --> 00:13:09.250 align:middle line:84%
So this stops you
from being motivated.

00:13:09.250 --> 00:13:12.080 align:middle line:84%
It turns off the
reward centers and that

00:13:12.080 --> 00:13:13.800 align:middle line:90%
shuts down consciousness.

00:13:13.800 --> 00:13:16.560 align:middle line:84%
So this is the coolest
thing in neuroscience.

00:13:16.560 --> 00:13:19.000 align:middle line:84%
Every negative thought
and feeling you have

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.580 align:middle line:84%
interferes with the
process of you solving

00:13:21.580 --> 00:13:24.040 align:middle line:84%
any problem that's
about to come up.

00:13:24.040 --> 00:13:26.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So when someone
says be in present time,

00:13:26.440 --> 00:13:29.317 align:middle line:84%
where you're not being attacked
or in fear or the negative

00:13:29.317 --> 00:13:31.400 align:middle line:84%
experience is not happening
at this very moment,--

00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:31.630 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: You have to train it.

00:13:31.630 --> 00:13:33.645 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --that actually
allows you to--

00:13:33.645 --> 00:13:34.270 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:13:34.270 --> 00:13:37.399 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --get to the next moment
with some cognitive processing.

00:13:37.399 --> 00:13:39.440 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: And it's very
easy to train your brain

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:40.710 align:middle line:90%
to come into the present moment.

00:13:40.710 --> 00:13:40.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

00:13:40.980 --> 00:13:42.980 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: But this feels
very unusual to do so.

00:13:42.980 --> 00:13:45.105 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I mean this makes
so much sense when you're

00:13:45.105 --> 00:13:47.400 align:middle line:84%
trying to problem solve,
when you're stuck in grief,

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:48.900 align:middle line:90%
if you're in pain.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:51.310 align:middle line:84%
If you stick with
the present moment

00:13:51.310 --> 00:13:53.430 align:middle line:84%
and realize that
that is not happening

00:13:53.430 --> 00:13:56.290 align:middle line:84%
in that present moment, it will
give you the cognitive ability

00:13:56.290 --> 00:13:57.726 align:middle line:90%
to help solve the next moment.

00:13:57.726 --> 00:13:59.100 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Let's
give the viewers

00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:01.970 align:middle line:84%
an actual sense of how you
can change your consciousness

00:14:01.970 --> 00:14:04.350 align:middle line:90%
literally in 60 seconds.

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:05.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:08.434 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I know what this is.

00:14:08.434 --> 00:14:09.210 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: OK.

00:14:09.210 --> 00:14:11.060 align:middle line:84%
Now in our previous
book, "How God

00:14:11.060 --> 00:14:15.260 align:middle line:84%
Changes Your Brain" we found
that the fastest way to relax

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:16.140 align:middle line:90%
is to yawn.

00:14:16.140 --> 00:14:19.790 align:middle line:84%
And I have 43 documented studies
to show that yawning actually

00:14:19.790 --> 00:14:22.410 align:middle line:84%
lights up your frontal lobes
and other parts of your brain

00:14:22.410 --> 00:14:25.140 align:middle line:84%
that are involved
with consciousness.

00:14:25.140 --> 00:14:28.670 align:middle line:84%
But if everybody was to just
take a moment and just yawn.

00:14:28.670 --> 00:14:31.970 align:middle line:84%
And if you just move
around in slow motion

00:14:31.970 --> 00:14:34.640 align:middle line:84%
and even take your
hands and begin

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:39.870 align:middle line:84%
to touch your hands or your
face, in pleasurable moments,

00:14:39.870 --> 00:14:43.180 align:middle line:84%
you need to remember that
pleasure for the lower brain

00:14:43.180 --> 00:14:46.120 align:middle line:84%
is what motivates us to
take action in the world.

00:14:46.120 --> 00:14:48.137 align:middle line:84%
So just doing something
for a few seconds,--

00:14:48.137 --> 00:14:48.970 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:51.770 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: --breathing,
relaxing, creating

00:14:51.770 --> 00:14:55.220 align:middle line:84%
some pleasure, this
is releasing dopamine.

00:14:55.220 --> 00:14:57.120 align:middle line:84%
This brings you into
the present moment.

00:14:57.120 --> 00:14:58.560 align:middle line:90%
It feels really good.

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:00.690 align:middle line:90%
Your brain wants more of it.

00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:02.760 align:middle line:90%
So it's very practical.

00:15:02.760 --> 00:15:07.640 align:middle line:84%
We can now apply this to a
very stressful work situation.

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:10.090 align:middle line:84%
Work as hard as
you possibly can.

00:15:10.090 --> 00:15:12.880 align:middle line:84%
But when the moment you begin
to feel some stress, which

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:15.340 align:middle line:84%
is those neurochemicals
shutting down

00:15:15.340 --> 00:15:19.180 align:middle line:84%
the motivational center of
your brain, then take a moment,

00:15:19.180 --> 00:15:22.230 align:middle line:84%
take a few deep breaths,
do something pleasurable,

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:24.980 align:middle line:84%
go give yourself a hug or get
a hug from somebody that you

00:15:24.980 --> 00:15:29.150 align:middle line:84%
like, do anything that gives you
a momentary sense of pleasure.

00:15:29.150 --> 00:15:31.110 align:middle line:84%
This literally
refreshes your brain.

00:15:31.110 --> 00:15:33.530 align:middle line:90%
You get a burst of dopamine.

00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:35.420 align:middle line:84%
This is the best
drug in your brain.

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:37.210 align:middle line:90%
And that's absolutely free.

00:15:37.210 --> 00:15:38.740 align:middle line:90%
It wakes up consciousness.

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:42.050 align:middle line:84%
You can then go back into
work and work harder,

00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:44.239 align:middle line:84%
have higher productivity
with less stress.

00:15:44.239 --> 00:15:46.280 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well taking this
to another level though,

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:49.790 align:middle line:84%
isn't simulating those pleasure
centers of brain, stimulated.

00:15:49.790 --> 00:15:51.680 align:middle line:84%
And dopamine is
released by things

00:15:51.680 --> 00:15:53.225 align:middle line:90%
like buying something new,--

00:15:53.225 --> 00:15:53.850 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:54.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --shiny objects,--

00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:55.919 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Oh, God, yes.

00:15:55.919 --> 00:15:57.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --possibly pornography.

00:15:57.320 --> 00:15:57.590 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:15:57.590 --> 00:15:59.715 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: These types of
things stimulate and release

00:15:59.715 --> 00:16:02.270 align:middle line:84%
the dopamine in the
brain, don't they?

00:16:02.270 --> 00:16:04.590 align:middle line:84%
Is that why there
are shopaholics?

00:16:04.590 --> 00:16:05.270 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:16:05.270 --> 00:16:07.250 align:middle line:84%
This is the interesting
thing about the reward

00:16:07.250 --> 00:16:08.450 align:middle line:90%
system of the brain.

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:10.740 align:middle line:84%
We know that the three
most powerful images

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:13.890 align:middle line:84%
for human beings, first
of all are loving images.

00:16:13.890 --> 00:16:16.300 align:middle line:84%
Somebody hugging,
kissing, erotic images.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:19.060 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter whether
you're aware of it or not.

00:16:19.060 --> 00:16:21.555 align:middle line:84%
This stimulates your
lower brain into action.

00:16:21.555 --> 00:16:23.300 align:middle line:90%
It simply wants more of it.

00:16:23.300 --> 00:16:25.960 align:middle line:84%
The other one is whatever
your favorite comfort food is.

00:16:25.960 --> 00:16:29.470 align:middle line:84%
This really lights up the
lower centers of your brain.

00:16:29.470 --> 00:16:32.670 align:middle line:84%
And then the third
one is, if I show you

00:16:32.670 --> 00:16:36.200 align:middle line:84%
a picture of a single coin
for one fifth of a second

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:37.890 align:middle line:84%
while you're in a
brain scan machine,

00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:40.210 align:middle line:84%
whatever activity
you're doing, you'll

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:41.930 align:middle line:90%
do with more power and force.

00:16:41.930 --> 00:16:44.930 align:middle line:84%
And these are university
documented research studies.

00:16:44.930 --> 00:16:48.000 align:middle line:84%
So money, it turns out, is
unique for human beings.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.270 align:middle line:84%
The thought of wealth
drives us to work harder.

00:16:52.270 --> 00:16:56.280 align:middle line:84%
It's a pleasure center to
the lower part of our brain.

00:16:56.280 --> 00:16:58.520 align:middle line:84%
But understand
that pleasure, this

00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:00.880 align:middle line:84%
is just a momentary
form of happiness.

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:03.740 align:middle line:84%
There are other
levels of happiness

00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:08.349 align:middle line:84%
that transcend this basic
survival oriented thing.

00:17:08.349 --> 00:17:13.540 align:middle line:84%
So when you think about
peace, or integrity, or think

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:15.099 align:middle line:90%
of whatever your most sacred--

00:17:15.099 --> 00:17:16.170 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Happiness.

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:18.003 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: --your most
sacred word would be,

00:17:18.003 --> 00:17:20.640 align:middle line:84%
the things that you
desire most in life.

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:24.770 align:middle line:84%
These are very high,
abstract nouns and concepts.

00:17:24.770 --> 00:17:29.720 align:middle line:84%
If we can visualize what peace
looks like, what it feels like,

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:31.960 align:middle line:84%
then the motivational
centers of the brain

00:17:31.960 --> 00:17:34.300 align:middle line:90%
will begin to build models.

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:36.630 align:middle line:84%
And then we can use
our conscious minds

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:40.750 align:middle line:84%
to design strategies to get
more, and more, and more of it.

00:17:40.750 --> 00:17:43.990 align:middle line:84%
I call the motivational center
of the brain the M-drive

00:17:43.990 --> 00:17:46.610 align:middle line:90%
or the desire to acquire more.

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:49.072 align:middle line:84%
Because all mammalian
brains, no matter--

00:17:49.072 --> 00:17:51.030 align:middle line:84%
we get a little bit of
pleasure, you want more,

00:17:51.030 --> 00:17:52.020 align:middle line:90%
and, more, and more.

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:53.360 align:middle line:90%
And that comes to addiction.

00:17:53.360 --> 00:17:55.690 align:middle line:84%
If too much dopamine
gets released,

00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:58.250 align:middle line:84%
your behavior becomes
impulsive and then

00:17:58.250 --> 00:17:59.920 align:middle line:90%
you can't stop doing it.

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:02.330 align:middle line:84%
We could take probes
and put them right down

