Why should I even
waste my words?

00:26:33.690 --> 00:26:37.120 align:middle line:84%
But this is enough information
for you to hang on to.

00:26:37.120 --> 00:26:38.990 align:middle line:90%
You say something back.

00:26:38.990 --> 00:26:40.640 align:middle line:90%
You do this exercise.

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:44.620 align:middle line:84%
I have a CD that trains a
person to take that, through it.

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:48.390 align:middle line:84%
And within four minutes,
about 25% of the audience--

00:26:48.390 --> 00:26:51.320 align:middle line:84%
we may have 200 people in the
audience paired up, doing this.

00:26:51.320 --> 00:26:54.510 align:middle line:84%
One slow sentence,
breathe, relax.

00:26:54.510 --> 00:26:58.570 align:middle line:84%
Intuitively respond,
breathe, and relax.

00:26:58.570 --> 00:27:01.740 align:middle line:84%
Tears are running down
individuals' faces.

00:27:01.740 --> 00:27:06.020 align:middle line:84%
I'm about to go down to a
conference of attorneys,

00:27:06.020 --> 00:27:09.900 align:middle line:84%
mediating attorneys, because
I teach the whole Southern

00:27:09.900 --> 00:27:12.950 align:middle line:84%
California attorney
system how to do

00:27:12.950 --> 00:27:14.960 align:middle line:90%
this type of communication.

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:18.270 align:middle line:84%
And you have two highly
conflicted individuals.

00:27:18.270 --> 00:27:22.750 align:middle line:84%
And in mediation, if you have
one sentence in 10 seconds,

00:27:22.750 --> 00:27:25.290 align:middle line:84%
you're not going to get
emotionally wrapped up in that.

00:27:25.290 --> 00:27:26.180 align:middle line:90%
You give another.

00:27:26.180 --> 00:27:27.535 align:middle line:90%
The next person says a response.

00:27:27.535 --> 00:27:29.660 align:middle line:90%
The attorney says one sentence.

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:31.750 align:middle line:84%
In 20 minutes, we
can solve problems

00:27:31.750 --> 00:27:34.670 align:middle line:84%
that normally take two to
three hours of mediation.

00:27:34.670 --> 00:27:36.620 align:middle line:84%
And so money wise
that translates

00:27:36.620 --> 00:27:40.450 align:middle line:84%
from a $2,000 problem
into a $200 problem.

00:27:40.450 --> 00:27:42.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely fascinating.

00:27:42.390 --> 00:27:45.690 align:middle line:84%
So you had talked to me about
big ideas in the brain--

00:27:45.690 --> 00:27:46.540 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Oh, yes.

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:50.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --and how big ideas
really change the brain.

00:27:50.140 --> 00:27:52.160 align:middle line:84%
And what we're
taking a look at here

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:54.390 align:middle line:84%
is the frontal
thalamic connection.

00:27:54.390 --> 00:27:55.080 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:56.970 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is that where
the big ideas exist?

00:27:56.970 --> 00:27:58.690 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: This is
the most amazing thing

00:27:58.690 --> 00:28:01.290 align:middle line:84%
about frontal lobe
consciousness.

00:28:01.290 --> 00:28:05.930 align:middle line:84%
The more I immerse myself
in an idea, a value

00:28:05.930 --> 00:28:09.260 align:middle line:84%
that I hold really important,
a goal that I really

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:10.660 align:middle line:84%
want to achieve--
and by the way,

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:13.770 align:middle line:84%
it's very, very important
to be able to visualize it.

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:16.867 align:middle line:84%
If you can't have a picture
of what your big idea is,

00:28:16.867 --> 00:28:19.200 align:middle line:84%
the lower part of your brain
won't know how the respond.

00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:20.570 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't get turned on.

00:28:20.570 --> 00:28:21.830 align:middle line:90%
It just sounds like it.

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:23.790 align:middle line:84%
And so for something like peace,
that's kind of interesting.

00:28:23.790 --> 00:28:25.248 align:middle line:84%
You have to do a
little extra work.

00:28:25.248 --> 00:28:28.992 align:middle line:84%
You have to visualize
peaceful scenarios, scenes

00:28:28.992 --> 00:28:29.700 align:middle line:90%
that create that.

00:28:29.700 --> 00:28:32.290 align:middle line:84%
You might want to
imagine yourself sitting

00:28:32.290 --> 00:28:35.620 align:middle line:84%
with a very incredible, peaceful
expression on your face.

00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:36.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What about love?

00:28:36.620 --> 00:28:37.500 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: The same with love.

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:38.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Same thing.

00:28:38.150 --> 00:28:39.399 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: You need a picture.

00:28:39.399 --> 00:28:43.110 align:middle line:84%
With the picture, now
your brain gets pleasure

00:28:43.110 --> 00:28:44.720 align:middle line:90%
from that picture.

00:28:44.720 --> 00:28:47.060 align:middle line:84%
That dopamine raises
consciousness.

00:28:47.060 --> 00:28:49.160 align:middle line:84%
The frontal lobe
processes now can

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:52.790 align:middle line:84%
create strategies to
move towards that goal.

00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:55.430 align:middle line:84%
As long as your
brain knows that you

00:28:55.430 --> 00:28:59.050 align:middle line:84%
were moving towards the goal,
more dopamine gets released.

00:28:59.050 --> 00:29:01.690 align:middle line:84%
That's what keeps you
going throughout your goal.

00:29:01.690 --> 00:29:04.440 align:middle line:84%
Again, bring in the slightest
negative thought, "oh,

00:29:04.440 --> 00:29:06.100 align:middle line:90%
maybe I won't succeed."

00:29:06.100 --> 00:29:08.020 align:middle line:84%
And then what you are
seeing in this picture,

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:09.390 align:middle line:90%
I have that thought.

00:29:09.390 --> 00:29:10.800 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I won't succeed.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:12.650 align:middle line:84%
That information
is sent into one

00:29:12.650 --> 00:29:14.620 align:middle line:84%
of the deeper parts
of the brain here.

00:29:14.620 --> 00:29:16.380 align:middle line:90%
This is the thalamus.

00:29:16.380 --> 00:29:18.980 align:middle line:84%
The thalamus, most
people used to think just

00:29:18.980 --> 00:29:21.010 align:middle line:90%
processes sensory information.

00:29:21.010 --> 00:29:23.380 align:middle line:84%
So something you see,
or hear, or smell,

00:29:23.380 --> 00:29:24.500 align:middle line:90%
it goes to the thalamus.

00:29:24.500 --> 00:29:26.420 align:middle line:84%
And you can see all
of the connections

00:29:26.420 --> 00:29:28.100 align:middle line:84%
that the thalamus
sends this information

00:29:28.100 --> 00:29:30.420 align:middle line:84%
to all the rest of the
parts of the brain.

00:29:30.420 --> 00:29:32.210 align:middle line:84%
But the thalamus deals
with every thought

00:29:32.210 --> 00:29:35.300 align:middle line:84%
you have as if it's a
real sensation coming in

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:36.930 align:middle line:90%
from the outside world.

00:29:36.930 --> 00:29:41.070 align:middle line:84%
It does not distinguish between
imagination and reality.

00:29:41.070 --> 00:29:45.710 align:middle line:84%
So if you imagine you're going
to be successful at achieving

00:29:45.710 --> 00:29:50.610 align:middle line:84%
any goal that brings you a sense
of pleasure and satisfaction,

00:29:50.610 --> 00:29:52.870 align:middle line:84%
that information goes
out to your brain,

00:29:52.870 --> 00:29:55.350 align:middle line:84%
boom, a great
release of dopamine.

00:29:55.350 --> 00:29:57.690 align:middle line:84%
Suddenly you find
yourself climbing out

00:29:57.690 --> 00:30:01.610 align:middle line:84%
of your chair to go do that
because your lower brain is

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:03.430 align:middle line:90%
greedy and selfish and hungry.

00:30:03.430 --> 00:30:07.230 align:middle line:84%
And it wants more of that thing
called peace, or happiness,

00:30:07.230 --> 00:30:10.050 align:middle line:84%
or success in any way
you want to imagine it.

00:30:10.050 --> 00:30:12.991 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is that kind of how the
law of attraction might work?

00:30:12.991 --> 00:30:15.240 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: This is the
neurological law of attraction.

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:16.031 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Attraction.

00:30:16.031 --> 00:30:18.350 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: So in
your mind, whatever

00:30:18.350 --> 00:30:20.170 align:middle line:84%
you think, the
rest of your brain

00:30:20.170 --> 00:30:22.040 align:middle line:84%
is going to assume
that that's reality.

00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:22.570 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Hm.

00:30:22.570 --> 00:30:23.324 align:middle line:90%
That is true.

00:30:23.324 --> 00:30:25.490 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: And again, the
slightest negative thought

00:30:25.490 --> 00:30:28.820 align:middle line:84%
causes a bit of a
frown in your face.

00:30:28.820 --> 00:30:31.470 align:middle line:84%
And the moment another
human being sees--

00:30:31.470 --> 00:30:34.590 align:middle line:84%
remember when I said that
words were number eight?

00:30:34.590 --> 00:30:37.110 align:middle line:90%
Number one is facial expression.

00:30:37.110 --> 00:30:40.950 align:middle line:84%
And Paul Ekman has identified
10,000 facial expressions.

00:30:40.950 --> 00:30:43.410 align:middle line:84%
But there's only one
facial expression

00:30:43.410 --> 00:30:46.210 align:middle line:84%
that creates
instantaneous trust.

00:30:46.210 --> 00:30:49.110 align:middle line:84%
And this is what we describe in
a whole chapter of this book.

00:30:49.110 --> 00:30:51.630 align:middle line:84%
And so we created one
specific exercise.

00:30:51.630 --> 00:30:55.270 align:middle line:84%
And this is what we teach on
day one, class number one,

00:30:55.270 --> 00:30:58.660 align:middle line:84%
to all of the executive MBA
students at Loyola Marymount

00:30:58.660 --> 00:30:59.340 align:middle line:90%
University.

00:30:59.340 --> 00:31:02.140 align:middle line:84%
We ask a person to close their
eyes, take a deep breath,

00:31:02.140 --> 00:31:03.010 align:middle line:90%
relax.

00:31:03.010 --> 00:31:07.880 align:middle line:84%
And ask them, what is your
deepest, innermost value?

00:31:07.880 --> 00:31:09.470 align:middle line:84%
And we ask them
to do this for one

00:31:09.470 --> 00:31:12.000 align:middle line:84%
minute, every
morning for 10 days.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:15.390 align:middle line:84%
Many people will say
what kind of New Age

00:31:15.390 --> 00:31:17.600 align:middle line:90%
hocus pocus BS is this?

00:31:17.600 --> 00:31:22.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, BS can be brain
science, or not.

00:31:22.180 --> 00:31:26.130 align:middle line:84%
But by about day five--
we've done this now

00:31:26.130 --> 00:31:28.490 align:middle line:84%
for four years--
90% of the students

00:31:28.490 --> 00:31:31.710 align:middle line:84%
say this exercise should be
taught to every MBA student

00:31:31.710 --> 00:31:32.910 align:middle line:90%
across America.

00:31:32.910 --> 00:31:35.630 align:middle line:84%
Because what we
found happened is

00:31:35.630 --> 00:31:38.740 align:middle line:84%
that by focusing for one
minute on what your deepest,

00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:43.020 align:middle line:84%
innermost value is for that
day, it reduces the stress

00:31:43.020 --> 00:31:44.880 align:middle line:84%
throughout the whole
rest of the work day.

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:47.000 align:middle line:84%
And executive MBA
students-- these

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.910 align:middle line:84%
are people already running
$1 million, $10 million,

00:31:49.910 --> 00:31:51.690 align:middle line:90%
$100 million companies.

00:31:51.690 --> 00:31:53.740 align:middle line:84%
They're working 10,
12, 14 hours a day.

00:31:53.740 --> 00:31:54.365 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Um-huh.

00:31:54.365 --> 00:31:54.880 align:middle line:90%
Um-huh.

00:31:54.880 --> 00:31:57.463 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: And for one person,
the word that came up for them,

00:31:57.463 --> 00:31:59.160 align:middle line:90%
their deepest value was family.

00:31:59.160 --> 00:32:01.690 align:middle line:84%
And by doing that
exercise-- he was a CEO--

00:32:01.690 --> 00:32:04.100 align:middle line:84%
he realized it wasn't
worthwhile spending

00:32:04.100 --> 00:32:05.750 align:middle line:90%
12 hours in the office.

00:32:05.750 --> 00:32:09.630 align:middle line:84%
So he cut back three hours
and devoted those three hours

00:32:09.630 --> 00:32:11.540 align:middle line:90%
to his sacred value.

00:32:11.540 --> 00:32:13.450 align:middle line:84%
This is your own
inner spirituality.

00:32:13.450 --> 00:32:16.930 align:middle line:84%
Your inner values is
your own inner religion.

00:32:16.930 --> 00:32:19.890 align:middle line:84%
Because we all have spiritual
circuits in our brain

00:32:19.890 --> 00:32:23.040 align:middle line:84%
that are based upon
our highest ideals

00:32:23.040 --> 00:32:26.170 align:middle line:84%
that take us beyond the
moment to moment happiness

00:32:26.170 --> 00:32:28.340 align:middle line:84%
to the deeper levels
of satisfaction.

00:32:28.340 --> 00:32:30.760 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And this is how
you spend 12 minutes a day

00:32:30.760 --> 00:32:33.290 align:middle line:90%
discovering your greatest value.

00:32:33.290 --> 00:32:35.140 align:middle line:84%
And that helps you
get rid of anxiety.

00:32:35.140 --> 00:32:38.490 align:middle line:84%
If your value is health, that
can help you with weight loss.

00:32:38.490 --> 00:32:40.070 align:middle line:84%
If your value is
spirituality, that

00:32:40.070 --> 00:32:42.265 align:middle line:90%
can help you with relationships.

00:32:42.265 --> 00:32:43.600 align:middle line:90%
It's across the board this way.

00:32:43.600 --> 00:32:44.500 align:middle line:90%
It's fascinating.

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:46.374 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Eating, yeah,
eating is wonderful.

00:32:46.374 --> 00:32:49.250 align:middle line:84%
If you-- in slow motion-- you
take a look at meditation.

00:32:49.250 --> 00:32:50.730 align:middle line:90%
What's involved in meditation?

00:32:50.730 --> 00:32:52.990 align:middle line:84%
Many times you're just
slowing down the process.

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:55.810 align:middle line:84%
So if you slowly
picked up your fork

00:32:55.810 --> 00:33:00.540 align:middle line:84%
and you slowly took a small
piece of food onto the fork,

00:33:00.540 --> 00:33:02.690 align:middle line:84%
and then you study
it, and you watch it,

00:33:02.690 --> 00:33:05.910 align:middle line:84%
and you observe it,
and then hold it

00:33:05.910 --> 00:33:09.110 align:middle line:84%
on your tongue for
20 seconds, you'll

00:33:09.110 --> 00:33:12.930 align:middle line:84%
discover incredible
sensations and flavors

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:15.030 align:middle line:90%
you never noticed before.

00:33:15.030 --> 00:33:17.395 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Will you actually
get full faster that way?

00:33:17.395 --> 00:33:18.020 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:33:18.020 --> 00:33:21.020 align:middle line:84%
This will actually satiate
because so much pleasure

00:33:21.020 --> 00:33:22.200 align:middle line:90%
is being released.

00:33:22.200 --> 00:33:25.540 align:middle line:84%
The brain, again, works
on the pleasure principle.

00:33:25.540 --> 00:33:26.960 align:middle line:84%
What normally we'd
be doing, we're

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:30.170 align:middle line:84%
eating so fast, oh, there's
a bowl chocolate ice cream.

00:33:30.170 --> 00:33:31.710 align:middle line:90%
I love chocolate ice cream.

00:33:31.710 --> 00:33:32.820 align:middle line:90%
You're gobbling it down.

00:33:32.820 --> 00:33:34.660 align:middle line:84%
All you're doing is
eating your memory.

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:37.250 align:middle line:84%
You're not taking the
time to really experience

00:33:37.250 --> 00:33:40.530 align:middle line:84%
the color, the shape,
the textures, the tones.

00:33:40.530 --> 00:33:42.450 align:middle line:84%
By slowing things
down and meditating

00:33:42.450 --> 00:33:44.280 align:middle line:84%
on a single morsel
of food-- we've

00:33:44.280 --> 00:33:48.030 align:middle line:84%
done the first brain scan study
at University of Pennsylvania,

00:33:48.030 --> 00:33:51.730 align:middle line:84%
Andy Newberg and I. And you
can see deep down in your brain

00:33:51.730 --> 00:33:54.330 align:middle line:84%
a part of the caudate
nucleus that gives you

00:33:54.330 --> 00:33:57.265 align:middle line:84%
more conscious control
over what you want to eat.

00:33:57.265 --> 00:34:00.490 align:middle line:84%
You have more power to choose
to eat what you really want.

00:34:00.490 --> 00:34:06.380 align:middle line:84%
And now you can use your
sensation and pleasure senses

00:34:06.380 --> 00:34:07.676 align:middle line:90%
to eat what you really like.

00:34:07.676 --> 00:34:09.050 align:middle line:84%
And the more you
immerse yourself

00:34:09.050 --> 00:34:11.120 align:middle line:84%
into what gives you the
most amount of pleasure,

00:34:11.120 --> 00:34:13.534 align:middle line:84%
the less you eat because
you get satisfied quicker.

00:34:13.534 --> 00:34:14.159 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Faster.

00:34:14.159 --> 00:34:17.340 align:middle line:84%
Most of us eat at our desks,
or driving, fast foods.

00:34:17.340 --> 00:34:21.370 align:middle line:84%
That pleasure center of the
brain is never stimulated.

00:34:21.370 --> 00:34:22.870 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: We
forget how important

00:34:22.870 --> 00:34:24.144 align:middle line:90%
that momentary pleasure is.

00:34:24.144 --> 00:34:26.144 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So this is dieting
through mind control.

00:34:26.144 --> 00:34:27.219 align:middle line:90%
I like it.

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:28.070 align:middle line:90%
That works.

00:34:28.070 --> 00:34:28.570 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:34:28.570 --> 00:34:30.320 align:middle line:84%
So now on the
opposite side, what

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:33.664 align:middle line:84%
happens in the brain when
fear is simulated and pain

00:34:33.664 --> 00:34:34.500 align:middle line:90%
is stimulated.

00:34:34.500 --> 00:34:35.916 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Well,
that's why I want

00:34:35.916 --> 00:34:38.550 align:middle line:84%
you to take a look at this next
slide that we have up here.

00:34:38.550 --> 00:34:40.699 align:middle line:84%
These are the actual
neural connections

00:34:40.699 --> 00:34:42.639 align:middle line:90%
from the visual cortex.

00:34:42.639 --> 00:34:45.500 align:middle line:84%
So if you see an unpleasant
picture, which could simply

00:34:45.500 --> 00:34:49.960 align:middle line:84%
be your spouse frowning
at you or whatever else,

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:53.100 align:middle line:84%
or somebody's just anxious about
something, or whatever else,

00:34:53.100 --> 00:34:56.230 align:middle line:84%
these tiny
micro-expressions is enough.

00:34:56.230 --> 00:34:58.820 align:middle line:84%
And you can see that the
neural circuits actually

00:34:58.820 --> 00:35:01.790 align:middle line:84%
go all the way down into
the center of the brain.

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:04.540 align:middle line:84%
And there's a little
tiny part of the brain

00:35:04.540 --> 00:35:06.230 align:middle line:90%
there called the amygdala.

00:35:06.230 --> 00:35:08.700 align:middle line:84%
And in Greek, "amygdala"
stands for almond.

00:35:08.700 --> 00:35:11.350 align:middle line:84%
And that is the part of your
brain that makes you go nuts.

00:35:11.350 --> 00:35:13.330 align:middle line:84%
So this sends sends
out a warning system

00:35:13.330 --> 00:35:15.610 align:middle line:90%
saying stop, potential danger.

00:35:15.610 --> 00:35:18.510 align:middle line:84%
And it sits right next to the--
motivation center starts right

00:35:18.510 --> 00:35:21.430 align:middle line:84%
at that point where
that green line ends.

00:35:21.430 --> 00:35:25.560 align:middle line:84%
So that literally turns off the
motivation center that quickly.

00:35:25.560 --> 00:35:27.350 align:middle line:90%
So it's on, off, on, off.

00:35:27.350 --> 00:35:30.970 align:middle line:84%
Bring in a pleasurable
image, the pain,

00:35:30.970 --> 00:35:33.680 align:middle line:90%
fear circuit gets turned off.

00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:36.540 align:middle line:84%
And now focus on a
pleasurable image, somebody

00:35:36.540 --> 00:35:38.950 align:middle line:84%
that you deeply
love and care for.

00:35:38.950 --> 00:35:40.470 align:middle line:84%
The more you hold
that image, you'll

00:35:40.470 --> 00:35:43.390 align:middle line:84%
see a Mona Lisa smile
form along in your face.

00:35:43.390 --> 00:35:45.870 align:middle line:84%
This is a whole separate
chapter that we do on that.

00:35:45.870 --> 00:35:49.350 align:middle line:84%
And that half smile is what
will make the other person

00:35:49.350 --> 00:35:52.526 align:middle line:84%
neurologically trust you
the moment they see it.

00:35:52.526 --> 00:35:55.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is the image.

00:35:55.050 --> 00:35:56.000 align:middle line:90%
How fascinating.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:56.920 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:35:56.920 --> 00:35:58.620 align:middle line:84%
And those are
involuntary muscles.

00:35:58.620 --> 00:36:00.980 align:middle line:84%
So again, the exercise
is very simple.

00:36:00.980 --> 00:36:03.840 align:middle line:84%
Just take a minute to think
about somebody you deeply

00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:06.910 align:middle line:84%
love and care for or an
event that brings you

00:36:06.910 --> 00:36:09.400 align:middle line:90%
deep satisfaction from the past.

00:36:09.400 --> 00:36:13.990 align:middle line:84%
That memory is enough to
create that half smile.

00:36:13.990 --> 00:36:17.310 align:middle line:84%
You'll feel that pleasurable
release of dopamine.

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:18.850 align:middle line:84%
The other person's
brain-- and this

00:36:18.850 --> 00:36:20.560 align:middle line:90%
is called neural resonance.

00:36:20.560 --> 00:36:23.300 align:middle line:84%
This is the way in which
we understand each other.

00:36:23.300 --> 00:36:27.700 align:middle line:84%
Your brain will begin to fire
in the way my brain is firing.

00:36:27.700 --> 00:36:30.930 align:middle line:84%
And so if I'm having
pleasurable, loving,

00:36:30.930 --> 00:36:33.800 align:middle line:84%
compassionate thoughts,
the same circuits

00:36:33.800 --> 00:36:36.015 align:middle line:84%
will begin to fire
in your brain.

00:36:36.015 --> 00:36:38.829 align:middle line:84%
Then we'll literally be
on the same brainwave.

00:36:38.829 --> 00:36:40.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's what that means.

00:36:40.120 --> 00:36:42.460 align:middle line:84%
And that's why the Mona
Lisa smile is so popular

00:36:42.460 --> 00:36:45.290 align:middle line:84%
is because it's such an
affirming, peaceful look.

00:36:45.290 --> 00:36:46.010 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:36:46.010 --> 00:36:46.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: All right.

00:36:46.760 --> 00:36:50.350 align:middle line:84%
So what happens when the brain
gets confused, and diffused,

00:36:50.350 --> 00:36:52.990 align:middle line:84%
and scattered, and
ADD, and all of that?

00:36:52.990 --> 00:36:55.487 align:middle line:84%
What does that look
like, lack of focus?

00:36:55.487 --> 00:36:57.320 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: This is the
other important thing

00:36:57.320 --> 00:36:59.930 align:middle line:84%
that we've just discovered
about the frontal lobes.

00:36:59.930 --> 00:37:02.410 align:middle line:84%
It looks like the
right frontal lobe

00:37:02.410 --> 00:37:05.230 align:middle line:84%
spends a lot of
its time processing

00:37:05.230 --> 00:37:09.490 align:middle line:84%
negative fantasies, so your
self-doubts, your worries

00:37:09.490 --> 00:37:10.510 align:middle line:90%
and fears.

00:37:10.510 --> 00:37:12.170 align:middle line:84%
These are just
imaginary thoughts.

00:37:12.170 --> 00:37:13.420 align:middle line:90%
Well, what if this went wrong?

00:37:13.420 --> 00:37:14.465 align:middle line:90%
What if that went wrong?

00:37:14.465 --> 00:37:15.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Un-huh.

00:37:15.090 --> 00:37:17.220 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Now with
that information,

00:37:17.220 --> 00:37:20.350 align:middle line:84%
your left frontal lobe should be
saying well if that went wrong,

00:37:20.350 --> 00:37:23.370 align:middle line:84%
I could do A, B, C,
and D. So it looks

00:37:23.370 --> 00:37:26.610 align:middle line:84%
like your left frontal
lobe is the optimist

00:37:26.610 --> 00:37:29.005 align:middle line:84%
and your right frontal
lobe is more the pessimist.

00:37:29.005 --> 00:37:31.296 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The problem is that
the right frontal lobe gets

00:37:31.296 --> 00:37:34.290 align:middle line:84%
more exercise than
the left, by having

00:37:34.290 --> 00:37:37.077 align:middle line:84%
negative thinking and
shame, blame, guilt, fear.

00:37:37.077 --> 00:37:39.410 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: We don't have
enough information to say that.

00:37:39.410 --> 00:37:41.670 align:middle line:84%
But again, what we have
found from the meditation

00:37:41.670 --> 00:37:43.230 align:middle line:84%
studies, and
particularly the studies

00:37:43.230 --> 00:37:46.410 align:middle line:84%
by Ritchie Davidson at the
University of Wisconsin,

00:37:46.410 --> 00:37:48.930 align:middle line:84%
is that we see that
people who are doing

00:37:48.930 --> 00:37:52.160 align:middle line:84%
meditations focusing
on self-love,

00:37:52.160 --> 00:37:55.630 align:middle line:84%
and kindness, and
generosity and virtually

00:37:55.630 --> 00:38:02.000 align:middle line:84%
any form of gentle,
imaginary, or concentration--

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:06.280 align:middle line:84%
even yoga, for example,
you get the same kind

00:38:06.280 --> 00:38:08.060 align:middle line:90%
of brain simulation going on.

00:38:08.060 --> 00:38:11.460 align:middle line:84%
We see an increase in
the right frontal lobes.

00:38:11.460 --> 00:38:14.720 align:middle line:84%
So we know that positivity
is beginning to be built.

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:17.610 align:middle line:84%
And we see stimulation going
on in some of the newest

00:38:17.610 --> 00:38:20.850 align:middle line:84%
centers of the brain like
the anterior cingulate, which

00:38:20.850 --> 00:38:24.090 align:middle line:84%
is where compassion and
empathy begin to emerge.

00:38:24.090 --> 00:38:26.260 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so in
brain diffusion--

00:38:26.260 --> 00:38:29.010 align:middle line:84%
this is where the slide
that we're looking at here--

00:38:29.010 --> 00:38:31.210 align:middle line:84%
is the right and
left communicating?

00:38:31.210 --> 00:38:34.540 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Well, these are
new types of brain images

00:38:34.540 --> 00:38:37.740 align:middle line:84%
that are called brain
diffusion images.

00:38:37.740 --> 00:38:39.880 align:middle line:84%
So what we're doing
is being able to learn

00:38:39.880 --> 00:38:44.240 align:middle line:84%
how to actually map how
the connections from one

00:38:44.240 --> 00:38:47.414 align:middle line:84%
part of the brain, how
those neurons send out axons

00:38:47.414 --> 00:38:49.080 align:middle line:84%
and connect to other
parts of the brain.

00:38:49.080 --> 00:38:51.600 align:middle line:84%
And this is just
another image showing

00:38:51.600 --> 00:38:55.410 align:middle line:84%
how one small part of the
brain sends out information

00:38:55.410 --> 00:38:57.130 align:middle line:90%
to the whole rest of your brain.

00:38:57.130 --> 00:39:00.360 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And we have actually a
moving image of this as well,

00:39:00.360 --> 00:39:01.606 align:middle line:90%
where you can see--

00:39:01.606 --> 00:39:02.230 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:39:02.230 --> 00:39:03.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --from
different perspectives

00:39:03.500 --> 00:39:04.374 align:middle line:90%
what this looks like.

00:39:04.374 --> 00:39:05.320 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:39:05.320 --> 00:39:08.410 align:middle line:84%
So here you're actually
seeing the activity

00:39:08.410 --> 00:39:11.050 align:middle line:84%
that's going on in
your left hemisphere,

00:39:11.050 --> 00:39:13.530 align:middle line:84%
in specific, how it
connects through it, how

00:39:13.530 --> 00:39:16.320 align:middle line:84%
it weaves over and connects
with different parts going on.

00:39:16.320 --> 00:39:18.470 align:middle line:84%
And every different
activity that you do

00:39:18.470 --> 00:39:21.070 align:middle line:84%
is going to create a
different type of picture.

00:39:21.070 --> 00:39:24.610 align:middle line:84%
And again, remember even these
pictures, which should totally

00:39:24.610 --> 00:39:27.080 align:middle line:84%
change the way you've ever
looked at the brain before,

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:28.930 align:middle line:84%
is not an accurate
picture because this

00:39:28.930 --> 00:39:31.260 align:middle line:84%
looks like this is how
your brain is wired.

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:35.800 align:middle line:84%
So I want you to throw away
forever the word "wiring"

00:39:35.800 --> 00:39:38.930 align:middle line:84%
and substitute a brand new
word called "programming."

00:39:38.930 --> 00:39:41.511 align:middle line:84%
Because neural plasticity
is the new name of the game.

00:39:41.511 --> 00:39:42.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:39:42.010 --> 00:39:43.090 align:middle line:90%
This is what we get to see now.

00:39:43.090 --> 00:39:44.340 align:middle line:90%
I'm really excited about that.

00:39:44.340 --> 00:39:47.580 align:middle line:84%
These next images are what
neural plasticity actually is

00:39:47.580 --> 00:39:49.670 align:middle line:84%
and what it looks
like in the brain.

00:39:49.670 --> 00:39:52.990 align:middle line:84%
And you say that we have
creatures in our brain

00:39:52.990 --> 00:39:54.460 align:middle line:90%
that are actually neurons.

00:39:54.460 --> 00:39:55.970 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Oh my God, yes.

00:39:55.970 --> 00:39:57.865 align:middle line:84%
So in this first one,
I want to tell you

00:39:57.865 --> 00:39:59.740 align:middle line:84%
first of all we used to
think that there were

00:39:59.740 --> 00:40:01.259 align:middle line:84%
100 billion neurons
in the brain.

00:40:01.259 --> 00:40:03.050 align:middle line:84%
And we thought they
were kind of hard wired

00:40:03.050 --> 00:40:05.240 align:middle line:84%
and they kind of just
did the same thing.

00:40:05.240 --> 00:40:07.520 align:middle line:84%
Now we find out that
they are constantly

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:09.480 align:middle line:84%
moving around
throughout your brain.

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:10.980 align:middle line:84%
And at birth, they
can actually move

00:40:10.980 --> 00:40:13.021 align:middle line:84%
from the back part of the
brain to the front part

00:40:13.021 --> 00:40:13.720 align:middle line:90%
of your brain.

00:40:13.720 --> 00:40:16.220 align:middle line:84%
And different parts
continue to change.

00:40:16.220 --> 00:40:18.004 align:middle line:84%
Every time you
recall a memory, you

00:40:18.004 --> 00:40:19.170 align:middle line:90%
have a different connection.

00:40:19.170 --> 00:40:21.770 align:middle line:84%
You're never recalling
the same memory twice.

00:40:21.770 --> 00:40:23.930 align:middle line:84%
But we also have what's
called glial cells.

00:40:23.930 --> 00:40:25.760 align:middle line:90%
And "glial" used to mean glue.

00:40:25.760 --> 00:40:28.610 align:middle line:84%
But here I want to
see in this picture,

00:40:28.610 --> 00:40:31.490 align:middle line:84%
you can actually see
that these glial cells

00:40:31.490 --> 00:40:33.470 align:middle line:90%
are moving around neurons.

00:40:33.470 --> 00:40:36.770 align:middle line:90%
And they're fixing them.

00:40:36.770 --> 00:40:38.080 align:middle line:90%
They're healing.

00:40:38.080 --> 00:40:41.420 align:middle line:84%
They're kind of like
their personal masseuse.

00:40:41.420 --> 00:40:43.070 align:middle line:90%
They're massaging these neurons.

00:40:43.070 --> 00:40:44.960 align:middle line:84%
They're helping them
have more energy.

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:48.440 align:middle line:84%
They're recirculating some
of the neurotransmitters.

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:50.850 align:middle line:84%
They are the helper
cells in our brain.

00:40:50.850 --> 00:40:54.170 align:middle line:84%
And each one of our neurons and
each one of these glial cells

00:40:54.170 --> 00:40:55.990 align:middle line:90%
has a mind of its own.

00:40:55.990 --> 00:40:58.160 align:middle line:90%
It can learn new behaviors.

00:40:58.160 --> 00:41:01.430 align:middle line:84%
You can teach it to
learn new tricks,

00:41:01.430 --> 00:41:02.710 align:middle line:90%
move forward in the world.

00:41:02.710 --> 00:41:04.180 align:middle line:90%
You can traumatize it.

00:41:04.180 --> 00:41:06.425 align:middle line:84%
You can teach how to be
afraid of the environment.

00:41:06.425 --> 00:41:09.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And all that is
done through our thoughts--

00:41:09.170 --> 00:41:11.390 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: All of that
it is done-- yeah.

00:41:11.390 --> 00:41:12.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --and our environment.

00:41:12.110 --> 00:41:14.068 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: We can do that
through our thoughts.

00:41:14.068 --> 00:41:18.300 align:middle line:84%
And Eric Kandel won the
Nobel Prize in medicine

00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:20.650 align:middle line:84%
for taking a single
sea slug neuron

00:41:20.650 --> 00:41:23.430 align:middle line:84%
and showing that you can train
it to learn or traumatize it.

00:41:23.430 --> 00:41:25.450 align:middle line:84%
And this is true for every
neuron in your brain.

00:41:25.450 --> 00:41:27.075 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And we get
to see some of this.

00:41:27.075 --> 00:41:29.110 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: This is
very, very important.

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:32.390 align:middle line:84%
Here you're actually
seeing neurons

00:41:32.390 --> 00:41:35.170 align:middle line:84%
over a period of a few
hours actually reach

00:41:35.170 --> 00:41:38.620 align:middle line:90%
out, connect with other neurons.

00:41:38.620 --> 00:41:40.600 align:middle line:84%
So these are live
living creatures.

00:41:40.600 --> 00:41:43.060 align:middle line:90%
These are a community of people.

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:45.270 align:middle line:84%
You need to treat each
one of your neurons

00:41:45.270 --> 00:41:48.934 align:middle line:84%
as if it has a mind of its
own, a life of its own.

00:41:48.934 --> 00:41:50.600 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So these
neurons are connecting.

00:41:50.600 --> 00:41:52.290 align:middle line:84%
And this is what
neural plasticity is.

00:41:52.290 --> 00:41:52.670 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Correct.

00:41:52.670 --> 00:41:55.230 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And these are connecting
through thoughts, habits,

00:41:55.230 --> 00:41:58.820 align:middle line:84%
patterns, environment,
old memories.

00:41:58.820 --> 00:42:01.110 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: You damage one
part of your brain, the area

00:42:01.110 --> 00:42:04.120 align:middle line:84%
next to your brain is going
to start growing neurons

00:42:04.120 --> 00:42:06.600 align:middle line:84%
and connections in to try to
take over the function that

00:42:06.600 --> 00:42:08.627 align:middle line:84%
was lost, after a
stroke for example.

00:42:08.627 --> 00:42:09.460 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:42:09.460 --> 00:42:12.400 align:middle line:84%
So can you actually
ever regrow those cells

00:42:12.400 --> 00:42:13.950 align:middle line:90%
that are damaged from stroke?

00:42:13.950 --> 00:42:14.859 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:42:14.859 --> 00:42:16.400 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
we're working on now.

00:42:16.400 --> 00:42:17.775 align:middle line:84%
And the other cool
thing, and I'm

00:42:17.775 --> 00:42:21.280 align:middle line:84%
sure you've seen it in the
news, we can now put electrodes

00:42:21.280 --> 00:42:24.540 align:middle line:84%
into your brain
and these neurons

00:42:24.540 --> 00:42:26.250 align:middle line:84%
can connect with
those electrodes

00:42:26.250 --> 00:42:29.684 align:middle line:84%
to control a robotic
arm, or a computer,

00:42:29.684 --> 00:42:31.350 align:middle line:84%
and thought processes,
or whatever else.

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:33.872 align:middle line:84%
So you can use your
thoughts to communicate.

00:42:33.872 --> 00:42:34.830 align:middle line:90%
You could be locked in.

00:42:34.830 --> 00:42:38.620 align:middle line:84%
You may have lost all ability
to move your body, to speak.

00:42:38.620 --> 00:42:42.020 align:middle line:84%
Put a probe into the right
place and now you can actually

00:42:42.020 --> 00:42:45.230 align:middle line:84%
move cursors on a
computer and communicate

00:42:45.230 --> 00:42:46.370 align:middle line:90%
to the outside world.

00:42:46.370 --> 00:42:47.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, my goodness.

00:42:47.470 --> 00:42:48.761 align:middle line:90%
It's just so fascinating to me.

00:42:48.761 --> 00:42:52.360 align:middle line:84%
I had a brain injury and I
damaged the prefrontal right

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:53.570 align:middle line:90%
cortex of my brain.

00:42:53.570 --> 00:42:56.700 align:middle line:84%
And I was able to rebuild
it, through EEG though.

00:42:56.700 --> 00:42:58.270 align:middle line:90%
So it was doing just that.

00:42:58.270 --> 00:43:00.620 align:middle line:84%
It's a combination of EEG
working with neuroscience

00:43:00.620 --> 00:43:02.550 align:middle line:84%
and stimulating different
parts of the brain.

00:43:02.550 --> 00:43:05.272 align:middle line:84%
Now, I get to actually see
what the EEG was doing.

00:43:05.272 --> 00:43:07.230 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: When you had
that damage by the way,

00:43:07.230 --> 00:43:10.699 align:middle line:84%
did you notice any shift between
positive and negative thinking?

00:43:10.699 --> 00:43:11.990 align:middle line:90%
Did you feel happier or sadder.

00:43:11.990 --> 00:43:13.614 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I was just
thinking about that.

00:43:13.614 --> 00:43:15.210 align:middle line:90%
Yes, I lost my memory.

00:43:15.210 --> 00:43:19.730 align:middle line:84%
And so when I went through that
memory loss, I was in a blissed

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:20.770 align:middle line:90%
out state.

00:43:20.770 --> 00:43:23.580 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Because it was to
your right prefrontal lobe.

00:43:23.580 --> 00:43:25.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I damaged the
negative side of my brain.

00:43:25.580 --> 00:43:26.996 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: If it
was the left, you

00:43:26.996 --> 00:43:29.506 align:middle line:84%
might have had a much--
you might be living more

00:43:29.506 --> 00:43:31.162 align:middle line:90%
in a nightmare.

00:43:31.162 --> 00:43:32.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Thank goodness.

00:43:32.120 --> 00:43:33.210 align:middle line:90%
It's fascinating.

00:43:33.210 --> 00:43:38.640 align:middle line:84%
Because I realized it helped
me look towards optimistically

00:43:38.640 --> 00:43:39.920 align:middle line:90%
rebuilding my brain.

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:42.160 align:middle line:84%
And so I damaged the
negative center of the brain.

00:43:42.160 --> 00:43:44.160 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: And that's
what we do with our books,

00:43:44.160 --> 00:43:45.830 align:middle line:84%
and with our CDs,
and programs is

00:43:45.830 --> 00:43:48.960 align:middle line:84%
that we take the exercises
that we know so that you

00:43:48.960 --> 00:43:55.250 align:middle line:84%
can stimulate more of your
left frontal lobe processing.

00:43:55.250 --> 00:43:57.830 align:middle line:84%
Because that's where the
optimism and the decision

00:43:57.830 --> 00:44:00.370 align:middle line:84%
making takes place, in
creating a better balance.

00:44:00.370 --> 00:44:05.316 align:middle line:84%
And use other exercises so that
you get more activity and flow

00:44:05.316 --> 00:44:06.690 align:middle line:84%
going in key parts
of your brain.

00:44:06.690 --> 00:44:08.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I don't suggest
anyone to damage

00:44:08.500 --> 00:44:09.958 align:middle line:84%
your negative center
of your brain.

00:44:09.958 --> 00:44:11.720 align:middle line:84%
However, it is one
of the reasons why

00:44:11.720 --> 00:44:13.805 align:middle line:84%
I'm so committed to
getting positivity

00:44:13.805 --> 00:44:15.180 align:middle line:84%
and consciousness
into the world.

00:44:15.180 --> 00:44:15.790 align:middle line:90%
Fascinating.

00:44:15.790 --> 00:44:18.414 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Every time you start
worrying and doubting yourself,

00:44:18.414 --> 00:44:19.810 align:middle line:90%
you're damaging your brain.

00:44:19.810 --> 00:44:20.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: All right.

00:44:20.090 --> 00:44:20.330 align:middle line:90%
Oh.

00:44:20.330 --> 00:44:22.730 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: And understand that
those worries and fears have

00:44:22.730 --> 00:44:24.313 align:middle line:84%
nothing to do with
the present moment.

00:44:24.313 --> 00:44:26.250 align:middle line:84%
The easiest solution
to this, the next time

00:44:26.250 --> 00:44:29.922 align:middle line:84%
you find yourself being upset
about something, take a look.

00:44:29.922 --> 00:44:32.130 align:middle line:84%
You'll see that you're
pulling a memory from the past

00:44:32.130 --> 00:44:33.838 align:middle line:84%
and you're projecting
it onto the future.

00:44:33.838 --> 00:44:36.534 align:middle line:84%
I'm about to go home and tell
my wife that I dented her car.

00:44:36.534 --> 00:44:37.950 align:middle line:84%
Oh, no, how is she
going to react?

00:44:37.950 --> 00:44:38.950 align:middle line:90%
Is she going to get mad?

00:44:38.950 --> 00:44:40.840 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I said the
wro-- Take a moment.

00:44:40.840 --> 00:44:44.117 align:middle line:84%
Take a deep breath, relax,
come into the present moment.

00:44:44.117 --> 00:44:45.200 align:middle line:90%
None of that has happened.

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:47.830 align:middle line:84%
You don't know how your
wife is going to respond.

00:44:47.830 --> 00:44:49.870 align:middle line:84%
If you walk in through
the door and you're

00:44:49.870 --> 00:44:52.100 align:middle line:84%
filled with profound
love because you've

00:44:52.100 --> 00:44:54.550 align:middle line:84%
train yourself to do this
in the present moment,

00:44:54.550 --> 00:44:59.220 align:middle line:84%
your wife is going to
feel empathy for you

00:44:59.220 --> 00:45:02.480 align:middle line:84%
and that will temper
her hurt and pain

00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:03.620 align:middle line:90%
that you dented her car.

00:45:03.620 --> 00:45:05.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it really
is as simple as taking

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:06.984 align:middle line:90%
a deep breath and retraining.

00:45:06.984 --> 00:45:09.650 align:middle line:84%
When I get the images of what it
actually looks like-- sometimes

00:45:09.650 --> 00:45:11.608 align:middle line:84%
when I'm driving home
after a long day at work,

00:45:11.608 --> 00:45:13.500 align:middle line:84%
about two exits
before my exit, I

00:45:13.500 --> 00:45:16.379 align:middle line:84%
start to have anxiety about what
the house looks like, and got

00:45:16.379 --> 00:45:18.170 align:middle line:84%
to deal with the
homework, and cook dinner.

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:20.600 align:middle line:90%
And I get pretty--

00:45:20.600 --> 00:45:23.025 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: So try this exercise
and try it for seven days.

00:45:23.025 --> 00:45:24.900 align:middle line:84%
Each time you drive home
consciously choose--

00:45:24.900 --> 00:45:26.274 align:middle line:84%
and by the way,
traffic is great.

00:45:26.274 --> 00:45:28.630 align:middle line:84%
I always love what
Tetnal Han said.

00:45:28.630 --> 00:45:31.540 align:middle line:84%
The traffic gets all stopped up
and you see those red lights,

00:45:31.540 --> 00:45:33.920 align:middle line:84%
let that red light be
a reminder to stop,

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:36.190 align:middle line:84%
take a deep breath in, come
into the present moment.

00:45:36.190 --> 00:45:37.990 align:middle line:84%
If you're going
80 miles an hour,

00:45:37.990 --> 00:45:40.659 align:middle line:84%
you can't notice the
beautiful surroundings,

00:45:40.659 --> 00:45:41.950 align:middle line:90%
the trees that are on the side.

00:45:41.950 --> 00:45:44.989 align:middle line:84%
We have beautiful
freeways in LA compared

00:45:44.989 --> 00:45:46.030 align:middle line:90%
to the rest of the world.

00:45:46.030 --> 00:45:47.640 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There's a lot
of tree-lined freeways.

00:45:47.640 --> 00:45:48.020 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:45:48.020 --> 00:45:49.430 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Drive
home and imagine

00:45:49.430 --> 00:45:52.610 align:middle line:84%
all the wonderful,
pleasurable, enjoyable things

00:45:52.610 --> 00:45:54.860 align:middle line:84%
that you can and will
do when you go home.

00:45:54.860 --> 00:45:56.650 align:middle line:84%
And keep filling
yourself with that.

00:45:56.650 --> 00:46:00.062 align:middle line:84%
You'll feel so incredible
when you walk into the door.

00:46:00.062 --> 00:46:01.770 align:middle line:84%
And then you'll find
out that your spouse

00:46:01.770 --> 00:46:03.170 align:middle line:90%
hasn't done that at all.

00:46:03.170 --> 00:46:05.170 align:middle line:84%
And you'll will need
all that loving kindness

00:46:05.170 --> 00:46:06.500 align:middle line:90%
to help pull them.

00:46:06.500 --> 00:46:09.210 align:middle line:84%
You'll have a neural war
going on, neural dissonance.

00:46:09.210 --> 00:46:12.810 align:middle line:84%
You want them to resonate to
your peaceful and happiness.

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:16.330 align:middle line:84%
And you can do that as long as
you stay in the present moment.

00:46:16.330 --> 00:46:18.820 align:middle line:84%
Focus on the
wonderful sensations

00:46:18.820 --> 00:46:20.460 align:middle line:90%
that are always taking place.

00:46:20.460 --> 00:46:23.580 align:middle line:84%
Your worries, fears,
and doubts, 90% of them

00:46:23.580 --> 00:46:25.430 align:middle line:90%
are totally imaginary.

00:46:25.430 --> 00:46:28.070 align:middle line:84%
And we've learned how
to interrupt this--

00:46:28.070 --> 00:46:29.880 align:middle line:84%
because I do what's
called neurocoaching.

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:31.810 align:middle line:84%
And I can take a person
in less than an hour

00:46:31.810 --> 00:46:37.010 align:middle line:84%
and often times get rid of
10, 20 years of a bad belief

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:37.727 align:middle line:90%
system.

00:46:37.727 --> 00:46:39.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because you
know how the brain works

00:46:39.560 --> 00:46:40.360 align:middle line:90%
and what it looks like.

00:46:40.360 --> 00:46:42.760 align:middle line:84%
So we're getting the opportunity
to take a look at these images

00:46:42.760 --> 00:46:43.260 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:46:43.260 --> 00:46:45.277 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:46:45.277 --> 00:46:46.735 align:middle line:84%
This is really one
of my favorites.

00:46:46.735 --> 00:46:48.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is what we're
talking about right now, right?

00:46:48.510 --> 00:46:49.450 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:46:49.450 --> 00:46:51.610 align:middle line:84%
So what you're seeing
is how a neuron

00:46:51.610 --> 00:46:54.840 align:middle line:84%
decides to send out
axons to connect

00:46:54.840 --> 00:46:56.810 align:middle line:90%
with other neurons going on.

00:46:56.810 --> 00:47:00.990 align:middle line:84%
So these are actual film of
what are called neurites.

00:47:00.990 --> 00:47:02.380 align:middle line:90%
These are very young neurons.

00:47:02.380 --> 00:47:04.740 align:middle line:84%
Because we see the most
amount of movement taking

00:47:04.740 --> 00:47:07.390 align:middle line:84%
place in the brain
when we are young.

00:47:07.390 --> 00:47:09.500 align:middle line:84%
Most of your brain
is not very active.

00:47:09.500 --> 00:47:12.670 align:middle line:84%
And it's just incredible how
they connect and disconnect

00:47:12.670 --> 00:47:13.170 align:middle line:90%
all time.

00:47:13.170 --> 00:47:17.050 align:middle line:84%
When you understand that,
you'll understand that you never

00:47:17.050 --> 00:47:19.400 align:middle line:90%
recall the same memory twice.

00:47:19.400 --> 00:47:21.030 align:middle line:84%
And if you have
a negative memory

00:47:21.030 --> 00:47:24.680 align:middle line:84%
and you recall it while you
remain peaceful, happy, focused

00:47:24.680 --> 00:47:27.010 align:middle line:84%
on your deepest
innermost values,

00:47:27.010 --> 00:47:29.430 align:middle line:84%
that's what gets embedded
into that memory.

00:47:29.430 --> 00:47:31.090 align:middle line:90%
That goes back into storage.

00:47:31.090 --> 00:47:33.900 align:middle line:84%
And the next time something
triggers that memory,

00:47:33.900 --> 00:47:36.520 align:middle line:84%
you'll also bring up
a bit of the memory

00:47:36.520 --> 00:47:37.760 align:middle line:90%
of that peacefulness.

00:47:37.760 --> 00:47:41.990 align:middle line:84%
So our research shows that if
you spend one minute an hour

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:45.070 align:middle line:84%
throughout the day-- that's
about 12 minutes a day or just

00:47:45.070 --> 00:47:47.520 align:middle line:84%
do 12 minutes of
meditation solidly--

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:50.170 align:middle line:84%
but we find a lot of people
just don't like to do that.

00:47:50.170 --> 00:47:54.799 align:middle line:84%
So we think that you can do just
a bunch of short meditations

00:47:54.799 --> 00:47:55.590 align:middle line:90%
throughout the day.

00:47:55.590 --> 00:47:57.589 align:middle line:84%
We think that's actually
better because then you

00:47:57.589 --> 00:47:59.970 align:middle line:84%
get in the habit of always
training yourself to come

00:47:59.970 --> 00:48:02.350 align:middle line:84%
into the present
moment, feel refreshed.

00:48:02.350 --> 00:48:04.700 align:middle line:84%
This is what's being taught
at Harvard Business School

00:48:04.700 --> 00:48:05.970 align:middle line:90%
and at our school.

00:48:05.970 --> 00:48:09.370 align:middle line:84%
12 minutes a day,
eight weeks later

00:48:09.370 --> 00:48:13.440 align:middle line:84%
we see not only the beginnings
of major functional changes

00:48:13.440 --> 00:48:15.800 align:middle line:84%
taking place in
their brain, we see

00:48:15.800 --> 00:48:18.030 align:middle line:90%
structural changes taking place.

00:48:18.030 --> 00:48:21.990 align:middle line:84%
And in advanced mediators, you
can see functional changes,

00:48:21.990 --> 00:48:23.830 align:middle line:84%
in your frontal
lobe for example,

00:48:23.830 --> 00:48:26.140 align:middle line:90%
as high as 25% changes.

00:48:26.140 --> 00:48:28.270 align:middle line:84%
And in areas like
your thalamus, which

00:48:28.270 --> 00:48:31.440 align:middle line:84%
is shaping the reality in
which you think you live,

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:33.940 align:middle line:84%
you can change it
by as much as 10%.

00:48:33.940 --> 00:48:37.474 align:middle line:84%
We can actually look at a human
brain now and see what goes on.

00:48:37.474 --> 00:48:38.890 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So that's
what we're doing

00:48:38.890 --> 00:48:40.070 align:middle line:90%
today, which is fascinating.

00:48:40.070 --> 00:48:41.370 align:middle line:84%
I love that you're
sharing this with us.

00:48:41.370 --> 00:48:42.424 align:middle line:90%
So now, what is this?

00:48:42.424 --> 00:48:43.590 align:middle line:90%
What are we looking at here?

00:48:43.590 --> 00:48:45.840 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Here you're
looking at an unhealthy neuron

00:48:45.840 --> 00:48:47.220 align:middle line:90%
and a healthy neuron.

00:48:47.220 --> 00:48:48.740 align:middle line:84%
And this healthy
neuron is trying

00:48:48.740 --> 00:48:51.726 align:middle line:84%
to connect with
this poor neuron.

00:48:51.726 --> 00:48:52.600 align:middle line:90%
And we all have that.

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:55.030 align:middle line:84%
And it's just not
quite-- it just

00:48:55.030 --> 00:48:56.980 align:middle line:90%
isn't getting its act together.

00:48:56.980 --> 00:49:01.760 align:middle line:84%
So again, I think
it's fair to say

00:49:01.760 --> 00:49:03.290 align:middle line:84%
that if you look
in the human brain,

00:49:03.290 --> 00:49:07.560 align:middle line:84%
you see one of the most
amazing, cooperative communities

00:49:07.560 --> 00:49:08.930 align:middle line:90%
on the planet.

00:49:08.930 --> 00:49:11.320 align:middle line:84%
Neurons do not fight
with each other at all.

00:49:11.320 --> 00:49:12.903 align:middle line:84%
There's no hostility
going on in them.

00:49:12.903 --> 00:49:14.194 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They're always helping.

00:49:14.194 --> 00:49:15.780 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: They're
always helping.

00:49:15.780 --> 00:49:16.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Huh.

00:49:16.330 --> 00:49:17.746 align:middle line:84%
They're always
helping each other.

00:49:17.746 --> 00:49:20.260 align:middle line:84%
So they're always
helping grow, connect,

00:49:20.260 --> 00:49:22.020 align:middle line:90%
take care of the damaged ones.

00:49:22.020 --> 00:49:24.510 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: Create new
thoughts, seek new pleasures,

00:49:24.510 --> 00:49:28.760 align:middle line:84%
create greater satisfaction,
keep you driving through life

00:49:28.760 --> 00:49:32.140 align:middle line:84%
so that you have more of
both inner and outer wealth.

00:49:32.140 --> 00:49:34.835 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Could this be what a
goal looks like in the brain?

00:49:34.835 --> 00:49:38.310 align:middle line:90%


00:49:38.310 --> 00:49:43.070 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: The goal-- I have
a burst of pleasure going on

00:49:43.070 --> 00:49:45.470 align:middle line:84%
and my lower brain says
I want more of that.

00:49:45.470 --> 00:49:47.306 align:middle line:84%
Now, I have to use
my consciousness

00:49:47.306 --> 00:49:50.100 align:middle line:84%
to decide do I really
want more of that or not?

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:52.024 align:middle line:84%
I mean obviously, if I'm
trying to lose weight

00:49:52.024 --> 00:49:53.690 align:middle line:84%
and I have a bowl of
ice cream over here

00:49:53.690 --> 00:49:56.540 align:middle line:84%
and a bowl of carrots over
here, I have a real problem.

00:49:56.540 --> 00:50:00.010 align:middle line:84%
A suggestion, get rid of the
image of the bowl of ice cream

00:50:00.010 --> 00:50:02.990 align:middle line:84%
because I know how my brain
is going to respond to that,

00:50:02.990 --> 00:50:08.270 align:middle line:84%
and go with what brings you
pleasure in terms of focusing

00:50:08.270 --> 00:50:09.950 align:middle line:84%
on what your weight
loss goal is.

00:50:09.950 --> 00:50:13.290 align:middle line:84%
So what we have to teach
our hedonistic brain

00:50:13.290 --> 00:50:16.240 align:middle line:84%
is how to anticipate
a future pleasure.

00:50:16.240 --> 00:50:19.690 align:middle line:84%
So always make sure for any
goal you have, large or small,

00:50:19.690 --> 00:50:20.600 align:middle line:90%
two things.

00:50:20.600 --> 00:50:22.141 align:middle line:84%
One is you want to
make sure that you

00:50:22.141 --> 00:50:25.630 align:middle line:84%
give constant little pleasurable
rewards, every hour of the day

00:50:25.630 --> 00:50:28.060 align:middle line:84%
throughout the day, as you
move towards that goal.

00:50:28.060 --> 00:50:30.310 align:middle line:84%
And then make sure you have
a really nice, big reward

00:50:30.310 --> 00:50:32.390 align:middle line:84%
that you know is
going to satisfy.

00:50:32.390 --> 00:50:35.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the reward could be
the image of a healthy body.

00:50:35.960 --> 00:50:39.700 align:middle line:84%
The reward could be the image
of looking over the ocean

00:50:39.700 --> 00:50:42.670 align:middle line:84%
after you've bought the
ideal house of your dreams.

00:50:42.670 --> 00:50:47.477 align:middle line:84%
The reward could be how you
would look in that picture

00:50:47.477 --> 00:50:49.060 align:middle line:84%
that you take of
yourself or whatever.

00:50:49.060 --> 00:50:51.996 align:middle line:84%
Those are enough to
simulate the dopamine--

00:50:51.996 --> 00:50:52.620 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:50:52.620 --> 00:50:53.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --and the reward
centers of the brain.

00:50:53.730 --> 00:50:55.290 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: The brain doesn't
care whether it's a big--

00:50:55.290 --> 00:50:56.230 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So visualization
is powerful.

00:50:56.230 --> 00:50:57.605 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: --or
a small pleasure.

00:50:57.605 --> 00:51:00.370 align:middle line:84%
We tend to forget that
pleasure is something

00:51:00.370 --> 00:51:02.280 align:middle line:90%
that is absolutely essential.

00:51:02.280 --> 00:51:05.600 align:middle line:84%
And unfortunately, some
spiritual scriptures,

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:08.280 align:middle line:84%
they look at people who are
incredibly hedonistic and very

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:08.780 align:middle line:90%
selfish.

00:51:08.780 --> 00:51:10.820 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
downside of pleasure.

00:51:10.820 --> 00:51:13.340 align:middle line:84%
The more pleasure I feel,
the more pleasure I want.

00:51:13.340 --> 00:51:17.000 align:middle line:84%
And it becomes me, me,
me, me, me, me, me, me.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:18.810 align:middle line:90%
Now social forces come in.

00:51:18.810 --> 00:51:21.250 align:middle line:84%
And we have social
circuits in the brain.

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:25.760 align:middle line:84%
If we do not share our inner and
outer wealth with other people,

00:51:25.760 --> 00:51:28.780 align:middle line:84%
if we do not share our
kindness and generosity,

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:33.010 align:middle line:84%
if we do not share our material
wealth and with others,

00:51:33.010 --> 00:51:35.790 align:middle line:84%
others feel envious and
they will punish us,

00:51:35.790 --> 00:51:37.440 align:middle line:90%
even at a loss for themselves.

00:51:37.440 --> 00:51:42.670 align:middle line:84%
So there is a very interesting
socioneurological process

00:51:42.670 --> 00:51:43.900 align:middle line:90%
that takes place.

00:51:43.900 --> 00:51:48.310 align:middle line:84%
And we are forced-- if we
act greedy, we get punished.

00:51:48.310 --> 00:51:51.360 align:middle line:84%
But there are ways of--
like even if you simply

00:51:51.360 --> 00:51:55.080 align:middle line:84%
keep repeating may I be
happy, may I be well,

00:51:55.080 --> 00:51:57.190 align:middle line:84%
may I filled with
love and peace.

00:51:57.190 --> 00:52:00.260 align:middle line:84%
May you be happy,
may you be well,

00:52:00.260 --> 00:52:02.660 align:middle line:84%
may you be filled
with love and peace.

00:52:02.660 --> 00:52:06.420 align:middle line:84%
May we be happy, may
we be well, may we

00:52:06.420 --> 00:52:07.770 align:middle line:90%
be filled with love and peace.

00:52:07.770 --> 00:52:10.090 align:middle line:84%
This turns out to
be one most powerful

00:52:10.090 --> 00:52:12.500 align:middle line:84%
neurological
meditations we've found.

00:52:12.500 --> 00:52:16.190 align:middle line:84%
This stimulates a
part of the brain that

00:52:16.190 --> 00:52:19.500 align:middle line:84%
allows us to feel deeper
empathy and compassion.

00:52:19.500 --> 00:52:21.230 align:middle line:84%
And this part of
your brain is barely

00:52:21.230 --> 00:52:24.310 align:middle line:90%
functional before the age of 30.

00:52:24.310 --> 00:52:25.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, isn't
that interesting.

00:52:25.980 --> 00:52:28.640 align:middle line:84%
This could actually be the
secret to anti-aging as well.

00:52:28.640 --> 00:52:29.290 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Yes.

00:52:29.290 --> 00:52:29.790 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:52:29.790 --> 00:52:32.759 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So this
slide shows us the--

00:52:32.759 --> 00:52:34.300 align:middle line:84%
>>WALDMAN: So here's
a single neuron.

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:36.690 align:middle line:84%
And this neuron, this
is a very simple neuron.

00:52:36.690 --> 00:52:41.890 align:middle line:84%
It only has about maybe 10 or
12 axons at the tip going on.

00:52:41.890 --> 00:52:45.080 align:middle line:84%
And if you look closely, you can
actually see within the neuron,

00:52:45.080 --> 00:52:48.230 align:middle line:84%
there's all kinds
of flow going on.

00:52:48.230 --> 00:52:50.810 align:middle line:84%
There's all kinds of
neuroelectrical and

00:52:50.810 --> 00:52:53.050 align:middle line:90%
neurochemical activity going on.

00:52:53.050 --> 00:52:55.920 align:middle line:84%
And that information
worked its way to the tips.

00:52:55.920 --> 00:52:59.070 align:middle line:84%
And then the tips decide how
to connect with other neurons

00:52:59.070 --> 00:53:01.690 align:middle line:90%
to pass that information on.

00:53:01.690 --> 00:53:03.460 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So those--
that is actually

00:53:03.460 --> 00:53:05.396 align:middle line:90%
a memory that could be started.

00:53:05.396 --> 00:53:08.020 align:middle line:84%
And those little tentacles reach
out and connect with another--

00:53:08.020 --> 00:53:08.230 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Correct.

00:53:08.230 --> 00:53:09.856 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --neuron,
which forms a bridge.

00:53:09.856 --> 00:53:10.563 align:middle line:90%
>>WALDMAN: Right.

00:53:10.563 --> 00:53:12.490 align:middle line:84%
A memory is going to be
a collection of those.

00:53:12.490 --> 00:53:14.260 align:middle line:84%
And so we are at the
point that we now

00:53:14.260 --> 00:53:17.740 align:middle line:84%
know we can begin to extinguish
negative memories if we catch

00:53:17.740 --> 00:53:20.010 align:middle line:90%
them within the first 24 hours.

00:53:20.010 --> 00:53:21.950 align:middle line:84%
So we take a
traumatic event and we

00:53:21.950 --> 00:53:25.440 align:middle line:84%
do various forms of positive
thinking and neutralizing.

00:53:25.440 --> 00:53:28.480 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes just sitting back
and watching our thoughts,

00:53:28.480 --> 00:53:30.350 align:middle line:84%
and watching a
negative reaction,

00:53:30.350 --> 00:53:33.540 align:middle line:84%
while we stay deeply relaxed,
is enough to extinguish

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:35.195 align:middle line:84%
the formation of
a negative memory.

00:53:35.195 --> 00:53:36.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: One of the
